What is the Node.js Event Loop? 
-> Its a mechanism makes NodeJs able to make I/O opreations with non-blocking even NodeJs is single threaded.

2. What is Libuv and What Role Does It Play in Node.js?
-> Its a library written with "C" Language, it makes NodeJs able to non-blocking,
    it execute the Event Loop and use 4 threads as default for the libuv library 
    and it manages the process on the 4 threads if the process sync or will block another processes it will run on one of the 4 threads

3. How Does Node.js Handle Asynchronous Operations Under the Hood? 
-> NodeJs send the "async" to Libuv library , if the process DNS/crypto files will be send to the thread pool

4. What is the Difference Between the Call Stack, Event Queue, and Event Loop in Node.js? 
-> all work together 
    Call Stack : LIFO =  last function will be executed first (and this the only sync between them)
    Event Queue : The ready callbacks put in the Queue and exceuted after async or its time end
    Event Loop : It keeps his eyes on Call Stack if the call Stack is empty take the first callback in the Event Queue to exceute it

5. What is the Node.js Thread Pool and How to Set the Thread Pool Size?
-> The pararmeter in the Libuv library it the number of the threads that Libuv used to manage the async its 4 threads default and we change the number  
    with using enviroment variable called "UV_THREADPOOL_SIZE" in terminal or in the code file and it must be modified before the process start

6. How Does Node.js Handle Blocking and Non-Blocking Code Execution?
-> if the process will block another process it will be run on the Main Thread and the other process (async / the non blocking process) will be run on the Libuv threads
    (not all async processes will be send to Libuv => the network processes like HTTP Requests executes by the system directly (kernel level async))